  "text": "Stack protection mechanisms against buffer overflow attacks in LLVM are implemented across multiple components:\n\n**1. StackProtector Pass (llvm/lib/CodeGen/StackProtector.cpp)**:\nThe primary mechanism inserts stack protector checks into functions. The StackProtectorPass class (new pass manager) and StackProtector class (legacy pass manager) handle insertion of stack guard checks. The pass uses SSPLayoutAnalysis to determine which functions require protection and SSPLayoutInfo to track layout information. Main entry points: StackProtectorPass::run() and StackProtector::runOnFunction(). These insert code that loads a random stack guard value at function prologue and validates it at epilogue, calling __stack_chk_fail on mismatch.\n\n**2. Stack Protection Interfaces (llvm/include/llvm/CodeGen/StackProtector.h)**:\nDefines SSPLayoutInfo class that stores stack protection layout information including buffer size and protection flags, SSPLayoutAnalysis that analyzes functions to determine if they need protection, and the StackProtectorPass interface.\n\n**3. SafeStack Pass (llvm/lib/CodeGen/SafeStack.cpp)**:\nImplements separation of safe and unsafe stack allocations to prevent overflow attacks from affecting critical data. SafeStackPass::run() delegates to SafeStack::run() which splits the stack into safe stack (managed by normal LLVM code generation) and unsafe stack (allocated and managed through runtime library). This pass identifies unsafe allocations (e.g., large buffers, address-taken variables) and moves them to a separate dynamically allocated stack.\n\n**4. SafeStack Layout Management (llvm/lib/CodeGen/SafeStackLayout.cpp and SafeStackLayout.h)**:\nThe StackLayout class in the llvm::safestack namespace computes the optimal layout of unsafe stack frames, handling object placement, alignment, and lifetime-based coloring to minimize stack frame size and fragmentation.\n\n**5. Stack Check Failure Handler (libc/src/compiler/generic/__stack_chk_fail.cpp)**:\nProvides the runtime implementation of __stack_chk_fail() function that is called when a stack protector check fails. This function writes an error message and aborts the program. Header declared in libc/src/compiler/__stack_chk_fail.h.\n\n**6. Memory Safety Instrumentation (llvm/lib/Transforms/Instrumentation/AddressSanitizer.cpp)**:\nThe FunctionStackPoisoner struct instruments stack frames with AddressSanitizer, poisoning and unpoisoning stack memory to detect out-of-bounds access patterns and use-after-return bugs. This complements the basic stack protector with more comprehensive memory safety instrumentation through runtime checks.\n\nTogether, these components provide defense-in-depth stack protection: StackProtector provides canary-based detection of stack buffer overflows, SafeStack separates and isolates unsafe allocations, and AddressSanitizer provides comprehensive memory safety instrumentation during development and testing."
